Here's a complete implementation:

```csharp
// In Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Configure max request body size (slightly above 10MB to account for multipart overhead)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 11 * 1024 * 1024;
});

builder.Services.AddAntiforgery();

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseAntiforgery();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    const long maxSize = 10 * 1024 * 1024; // 10MB

    if (file.Length == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No file provided.");

    if (file.Length > maxSize)
        return Results.BadRequest("File exceeds 10MB limit.");

    var allowedTypes = new[] { "image/jpeg", "image/png" };
    if (!allowedTypes.Contains(file.ContentType, StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are allowed.");

    // Validate extension as a secondary check
    var ext = Path.GetExtension(file.FileName).ToLowerInvariant();
    if (ext is not ".jpg" and not ".jpeg" and not ".png")
        return Results.BadRequest("Invalid file extension.");

    var uploadsDir = Path.Combine(app.Environment.ContentRootPath, "uploads");
    Directory.CreateDirectory(uploadsDir);

    // Generate a safe unique filename
    var fileName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{ext}";
    var filePath = Path.Combine(uploadsDir, fileName);

    await using var stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Create);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName, size = file.Length });
})
.DisableAntiforgery(); // Remove this line if you want CSRF protection on this endpoint

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** is set to 11MB to allow multipart framing overhead above the 10MB file check.
- **Dual validation** — both `ContentType` and file extension are checked.
- **Unique filenames** via `Guid` prevent overwrites and path traversal attacks.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — remove this if clients will send a valid antiforgery token; keep it for API clients using bearer auth instead.

If you're behind IIS/IIS Express, also add to `web.config`:

```xml
<system.webServer>
  <security>
    <requestFiltering>
      <requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="11534336" />
    </requestFiltering>
  </security>
</system.webServer>
```
